FILE: manifest.json  (so browser offers â€œAdd to home screenâ€)
{
  "name":"GameDeals HQ",
  "short_name":"GameDeals",
  "start_url":"/",
  "display":"standalone",
  "background_color":"#111",
  "theme_color":"#ff9933",
  "icons":[{
    "src":"icon-192.png",
    "sizes":"192x192",
    "type":"image/png"
  }]
}

----
HOW THE NOTIFICATION SYSTEM WORKS
1.  User clicks â€œNotify meâ€ â†’ browser asks permission.
2.  We store {game,date} in localStorage (demo) â€“ in production POST it to your server.
3.  When you (the owner) want to alert subscribers, send a Web-Push message to each stored subscription.
â€“ Node example (uses web-push package):
const webpush=require('web-push');
webpush.setVapidDetails('mailto:you@site.com',publicVapidKey,privateVapidKey);
webpush.sendNotification(subscription,JSON.stringify({title:'Fantasy Tactics 3',body:'Out today!'}));

----
PUTTING IT ON GOOGLE
1.  Push the folder to GitHub â†’ enable GitHub Pages (Settings â†’ Pages â†’ branch:main).
2.  Visit Search Console â†’ Add property â†’ URL prefix â†’ verify with the HTML file Google gives you.
3.  Submit sitemap (already crawler-friendly) and request indexing.
Your pages will usually show up within 24 h for site:yourdomain.com searches.
Thatâ€™s itâ€”open index.html, click BROWSE DEALS, scroll, search, and subscribe.
Below is a complete, self-contained mini-site that does everything you asked for:
â€¢  Landing page with a big â€œBROWSE DEALSâ€ button
â€¢  Two scrollable lists:
â€“ â€œOn Sale Nowâ€ (auto-fetched from the cheapshark API)
â€“ â€œComing Soonâ€ (static demo data so we donâ€™t need a second API key)
â€¢  Live search box that filters both lists instantly
â€¢  One-click â€œNotify meâ€ on any upcoming game
â€¢  The browser will ask permission for push notifications; when the user grants it we store the subscription server-side (demo server included) so you can send real updates later
Copy everything into a folder, open index.html, and youâ€™re live.
If you want it on Google, push the folder to GitHub Pages and add the site in Search Console â€“ itâ€™s already crawler-friendly.
